places.name: Morne Rouge Beach
places.perex: This marvellous beach is often missed, but that makes it even more exquisite. Calm, clean and beautiful.

places.name: Fort George
places.perex: A fantastic fort. Learn about the history of the city in a fun way and enjoy the stunning views from the top.

places.name: Maurice Bishop International Airport
places.perex: Maurice Bishop International Airport, formerly known as Point Salines International Airport, is an international airport located in the…

places.name: Grand Etang National Park & Forest Reserve
places.perex: Grand Etang Lake is a crater lake in an extinct volcano. It is located on the island of Grenada, in Saint Andrew Parish.

places.name: Grand Etang Lake
places.perex: Grand Etang Lake is a crater lake in an extinct volcano. It is located on the island of Grenada, in Saint Andrew Parish.

places.name: Fort Frederick
places.perex: A nice and well-preserved fort. There is not much to see, but the views from the top are terrific.

places.name: Grenada Chocolate Factory
places.perex: Learn all about chocolate and how it is produced at this small factory. An interesting tour and a must for chocolate lovers.

places.name: Mount Qua Qua
places.perex: The mountain makes for a great hiking place - challenging, but rewarding. The views from the top are wonderful.

places.name: Grenada National Museum
places.perex: Explore Grenadian history and culture from all eras in this small but captivating museum. A little quirky, but interesting.

places.name: Underwater Sculpture Garden
places.perex: The Molinere Underwater Sculpture Park is a collection of ecological underwater contemporary art located in the Caribbean sea off the west…

places.name: Annandale Falls
places.perex: These beautiful falls are unfortunately quite touristy. However, they are well-accessible and still a stunning sight.

places.name: Spice Basket
places.perex: A theatre, restaurant and museum in one. A great way of exploring the Grenadian culture  in a number of different ways.

places.name: Pearls Airport
places.perex: Pearls Airport was Grenada's first airport, opened in 1943 located at the North Eastern Corner of the island of Grenada, 19 miles north…

places.name: Gouyave Nutmeg Processing Station
places.perex: Tour the factory and see how nutmeg is processed. And at the end, you can buy your own bag of fresh spice.

places.name: Black Bay Beach
places.perex: Named after the colour of the sand in this area, the beach is great not just for easy swimming but also for nearby cave-exploring.

places.name: Petit Bacaye Beach
places.perex: A secluded and sort of wild beach with grey sands and plenty of palm trees that provide shade. A romantic bathing spot.

places.name: Levera Beach
places.perex: A vast, sandy beach that is quite detached from any other parts of the island. The scenery is great here, too.

places.name: Seven Sister Waterfalls
places.perex: Also called St. Margaret falls, these seven natural wonders are well-worth the visit. An exciting and rewarding hike.

places.name: Mount Saint Catherine
places.perex: Mount Saint Catherine is a stratovolcano and the highest mountain on the Caribbean island of Grenada. It is located in St.

places.name: Petite Martinique
places.perex: Petite Martinique is een cirkelvormig eiland in de Caraïben dat deel uitmaakt van Grenada, maar geografisch in de Grenadines ligt.

places.name: Bay Gardens
places.perex: A true tropical wonder. These gardens are home to many species of plants from all over the islands.

places.name: Concord Falls
places.perex: There are actually three waterfalls here - do not miss the other two. A beautiful sight and you can even take a swim in the pond.

places.name: Clarke's Court Distillery
places.perex: Perhaps the best-known rum distillery on the islands. If you tour the factory, you will see their steam machines still in use!

places.name: Mt. Carmel Waterfall
places.perex: The highest falls on the island can be reached after a short hike through the lush nature. An inspiring sight well worth the visit.

places.name: Gun Point
places.perex: More of a curiosity. The 18th century cannon left here by the British gave the cliff its name. Great views.

places.name: Grenada Golf Club
places.perex: This 9-hole course offers not only stunning views of the sea, but also quite a challenge because of the wind.

places.name: Belmont Estate
places.perex: There is so much to do at this working cocoa plantation. A fascinating place where to learn about the history of the island.

places.name: The Aquarium
places.perex: An excellent restaurant situated in a beautiful waterfront spot. One of the greatest on the islands.

places.name: Bianca C Ship Wreck
places.perex: The Bianca C was a passenger ship that sank on two occasions, the first time in France before being completed, and the second time after an…

places.name: Sendall Tunnel
places.perex: Connects the two sides of town. It can get very crowded, since it's narrow, but that only adds to the experience.

places.name: Market Square, St. George's
places.perex: The main shopping hub of the city. There are many gems to be found here and there is a special section for the island's spices.

places.name: St. George's Anglican Church
places.perex: Even though the church was ruined by a hurricane, parts of it are still intact and make for a great sight.

places.name: Slipway Restaurant
places.perex: Delicious dishes made from local ingredients and served in an unusual setting - the restaurant is housed in former boatyard.

places.name: Hyde Park Tropical Garden
places.perex: The owners themselves will guide you through this private garden and tell you all about the plants here.

places.name: Dougaldston Spice Estate
places.perex: An old but charming estate well-known for its spice produce. A historical sight that also smells good.

places.name: BB's Crabback Caribbean Restaurant
places.perex: Mixes European and Grenadian cuisine, creating an unusual experience for anyone's tastebuds. Great location with views of the sea.

places.name: Bogles Round House
places.perex: This tiny village is home to a terrific restaurant. A new menu made from fresh ingredients is served here every day.

places.name: Westerhall Rum Distillery
places.perex: One of the prime distilleries on the islands. Come and see how rum is made and marvel at the old technology still in use.

places.name: The Beach House Restaurant
places.perex: If you've always wanted to try fine dining on an island beach, search no further. Delicious meals in a unique setting.

places.name: Carriacou Museum
places.perex: A tiny but welcoming museum featuring all about the history of the island, including some pre-Columbian artefacts.

places.name: Belair National Park
places.perex: The park features not only lush nature and breath-taking views of its surroundings, but also old Colonial buildings for you to explore.

places.name: River Sallee Boiling Springs
places.perex: These six springs are an intriguing geological formation and another evidence of Grenada's stunning nature.

places.name: River Antoine Rum Distillery
places.perex: The oldest still-functioning distillery on the island. Watch the making process and at the end, taste the rum for yourself.

places.name: Paradise Beach
places.perex: The beach is true to its name. A mile-long stretch of pristine sand and azure waters.

places.name: Grand Anse Craft and Spice Market
Dusquene Bay
places.perex: The sandy beach is the main attractions here, but there are also petroglyphs, left here by the natives in the cave nearby.

places.name: La Sagesse
places.perex: This secluded beach is one of the picture-perfect havens on this island. Just lay down on the soft sand and forget about all of your worries.

places.name: Lake Antoine
places.perex: The second largest lake on the island. Surrounded by unspoilt nature and banana trees.

places.name: Happy Valley
places.perex: This diving spot is made of a natural wall. A natural habitat for schools of fish, black corals and other marine life.

places.name: Levera National Park
places.perex: This protected coastal area is yet another of Grenada's stunning natural havens. Terrific both on land and in the sea.

places.name: Flamingo Bay
places.perex: A terrific dive site for both experts and beginners. There is really a lot of diverse marine life here.

places.name: Petit Carenage Beach
places.perex: A picturesque, solitary beach, surrounded by mangrove. The turtles lay eggs here, so don't disturb them while you visit.

places.name: Carib's Leap
places.perex: The last of the local natives, the Caribs, jumped to their deaths here after being surrounded by the French. An intriguing site.

places.name: Anse La Roche
places.perex: This remote beach might have no facilities, but its pristine sands and turquoise water more than make up for it.

places.name: Bathway beach
places.perex: Deserted most of the time, this beach comes alive when the local festivities take place here. Not many facilities here.

places.name: Lance aux Épines
places.perex: The quaint peninsula is one of the most beautiful parts of the island. Come visit its great beaches and friendly locals.

places.name: White Island Marine Park
places.perex: This small island is a true gem of Grenadine nature. White beaches, a small mountain on one side and the sea rich on marine life are its…

places.name: Tyrell Bay Beach
places.perex: The bay is lined by a pleasant beach more suited for evening strolls, since there are rocks underwater.

places.name: Fisherman’s Paradise
places.perex: Your chance to see dozens of fish at the spot where the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic meet. Suited for experienced divers.

places.name: Rum Runner
places.perex: The wreck of a former cruise boat is now inhabited by all sorts of marine life - you can even see angelfish here.

places.name: Magazine Beach
places.perex: The beach is popular because of its calm waters that make it suitable for families and also for enthusiastic snorkellers.

places.name: Northern Exposure
places.perex: This diving spot hides a sloping reef that is home to a variety of marine life. Lobsters, sponges, crabs and more to see here.

places.name: Laura’s Herb & Spice Garden
places.perex: The name says it all. The guide will tell you all about the island's spices and and other plants in the garden.

places.name: Hema 1 Wreck
places.perex: The ship sank only recently, but it's already becoming a popular marine habitat - look out for the sharks here!

places.name: Red Buoy
places.perex: Combine history and diving on this unique diving spot. There are many anchors scattered around here, some dating back to the 19th century.

places.name: Whibble Reef
places.perex: An extensive reef with lots of marine life you won't see closer to the shore. A rewarding and relaxing diving site.

places.name: Boss Reef
places.perex: The three mile long reef is rich on all sorts of marine life, from corals to schools of local fish or the occasional shark.

places.name: Unity Courier
places.perex: This wrecked ship has been broken in three parts. Each one of them is home to marvellous marine life such as rays or great anemones.

places.name: Japanese Gardens
places.perex: There is a real garden here - only underwater. See the fish and turtles swimming around the coral reef.

places.name: Buccaneer Wreck
places.perex: This wrecked ship is very much alive - there are schools of colourful fish, barracudas and even an octopus. A fun dive site.

places.name: King Mitch
places.perex: Experienced divers, do not miss this wreck. Far out in the sea, the fish and other marine life are really at home here.

places.name: Kapsis Wreck
places.perex: The currents are strong here, but experienced divers who explore the yacht will find turtles, sharks and other marine life here.

places.name: The Valleys
places.perex: The coral reef which connects to other dive sites is the home of sponges, eels, seahorses, angel fish and more.

places.name: Southern Comfort
places.perex: An easy dive with an opportunity to spot many kinds of marine life on this gently sloping reef.

places.name: Purple Rain
places.perex: This spectacular reef is simply brimming with all sorts of marine life. Barracudas, turtles and rays make this a great diving site.

places.name: Shark Reef
places.perex: The strong currents make this a challenging diving spot. However, the sharks, lobsters and other marine life here are well worth it.

places.name: Veronica L. Wreck 50’/ 15m
places.perex: A popular diving site - the wrecked ship looks very good both at day and at night and is an easy dive even for beginners.

places.name: High North Peak
places.perex: The island's highest peak has been declared a national park. There are several trails to follow and local animals to see.

places.name: Fiona Wreck
places.perex: An easy dive in shallow water. The wrecked barge might not look like much, but if you explore it thoroughly, you will find some marine life.

places.name: Kahonee Reef
places.perex: One of Grenada's picturesque diving spots - great for novices and underwater photographers. The reef here is brimming with life.

places.name: Grand Mal Bay
places.perex: Divers, look out for the MV Hildur here - she is now a haven for many schools of fish and also barracudas.

places.name: Hildur Wreck
places.perex: The ship was deliberately sunk here and barracudas together with other fish have already made it their home. For skilled divers.

places.name: Windmill Shallows
places.perex: One of the reefs surrounding Grenada. This one is home to both large and small marine life - even the sharks hang out here.

places.name: Oyster Beds
places.perex: Grenada's newest national park is home to dozens of oysters growing on the roots of mangrove.

places.name: Shakem Wreck
places.perex: The cargo ship has been here for only ten years, so it's still untouched by corals. A great wreck diving site.

places.name: Sandy Island Marine Park
places.perex: This island is beautiful both on land and underwater. The lush nature here combines with great diving and snorkelling spots underwater.

places.name: Quarter Wreck
places.perex: This wreck of a ship is a popular diving site, since it is easily explored and the fish and lobsters give it variety, too.

places.name: The Carenage
places.perex: St. George's harbour. Great for walking around, taking beautiful photos or just people-watching at one of the restaurants.
